text:
13 Sheridan Square, north side (135 Washington Place), an old frame house in the last stages of disrepair. The houses at the right are shortly to be demolished, but this one will stand until shortly after 1922. See 13, 14 Sheridan Square, the view about 1912 and the view taken about the same time as this one.
About 1920.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.
title: Manhattan: Sheridan Square - 158th Street (East)

text:
13-14 Sheridan Square, north side (135-133 Washington Place), an old frame house, which is said to have been a tavern, and now contains a curiosity shop.
About 1912.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, about eight years later, shortly before the demolition of all but the house on the left, which, it will be noted, has had a middle tier of windows cut in the Washington Place side of it.
About 1920.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.

Sheridan Sq. #10 - Barrow Street - Washington Place looking north

text:
3-4, 5 Sheridan Square, south side, at and adjoining the corner of Barrow Street. The Greenwich Village Inn is No. 5-6, which is not all included in the view.

May 1, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.
title: Manhattan: Sheridan Square - Barrow Street

text:
Greenwich Village Inn, 5-6 Sheridan Square, south side, between Barrow and Grove Streets, one of the oldest and best known of Village night clubs, since the closing of Don Dickerman's "Pirate's Den" on Christopher Street.

May 1, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.
